<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000460.html">boards.station.sony.com/u...00460.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
When the beastlord casts the level buff on their pet, it sets the current HP and Max HP of the their pet to the new number.  This effectively acts as a Complete Heal, but the spell takes longer to cast than the pet heal spells.  At certain levels, the pet heals are actually more mana efficient.  The levels that this bug benefits the most are 9-30, but at higher levels it is not actually used very much.<br>
<br>
Thorvari<br>
Vazaelle<br>
Vah Shir Beastlord <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uthuull.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thuull</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#333333>(7/3/02 5:48:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=259.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Beastlords Complete Healing their Pets</span><hr size=1> Another BST here:  I also want to point out that most BSTs don't play pet cleric...it takes too much time.  That would be like you guys sitting back and watching your pet fight every mob, without ever casting a nuke...the fights would take so long (if your pet lives) that it's just not worth doing.<br>
<br>
Most BSTs will stand up there and fight away with their pet.  The way pet aggro coding works, if the BST is solo, the mob will *always* attack the BST, no matter how much damage the pet does.  This means that the BST is the one taking the damage, not the Warder.  And, we don't have any bugs/exploits that cheal ourselves.<br>
<br>
So, it's really not beneficial to use.<br>
<br>
Agreed though that if it were usable by a Mage, it would completely own for you guys =)  But it doesn't matter for us because of the way we fight.<br>
<br>
Also, someone else pointed out that we can use charm items to charm a mob and buff him with pet spells.  Sure, it's kinda neat to have a moss snake as your pet...but the point is that no matter what you charm, when you buff it with your spells, it's exactly like your normal Warder...same damage, same hps, same everything.  All you have is a Warder with a new graffic.  This may also be considered as a bug/exploit by VI, and hence possibly warnable/banable...that being the case, there's no reason to do it at all...gets you nothing except the possibility that a GM will take exception to it.<br>
<br>
Thuull<br>
